extent.seg: 7 + 388 + 8 leaves. Some leaves are smaller or of irregular size as a consequence of being formed of off-cuts of parchment, but have nevertheless been counted in Extent (and are foliated).

foliation.p: Written in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the recto of each leaf by several hands of the 19th and 20th centuries (the latter apparently completing the former's partial sequence of foliation).
foliation.note: Folios 235a and 248a are partial leaves, after ff. 235 and 248 respectively. They have arisen from the use of off-cuts of parchment, and bear no writing. They were not previously foliated, but have now been numbered. They have not been photographed.

Folio 243a is a fragmentary leaf, after f. 243. It has arisen from the partial loss of a once whole leaf, and bears writing. As such, it has been foliated (albeit post-photography), and is included in the count of leaves in Extent.
Folios [i]-vii and 385-392 are original parchment endleaves.

The division of quires in the following collation deviates from the quire numbers added to the lower right-hand corner of the first leaf, or what was thought to be the first leaf, of each quire.

note.p: This collation deviates on a few points from the tentative collation that M.R. James has provided in his unpublished notes on this manuscript: James suggests that Quire 9 is missing one leaf but the quire, however, is a complete sexternion. While James tentatively identifies Quires 20-24 as sexternions, this collation proposes different structures at this point. While James suggests that his final quire, Quire 34, consist of 16 leaves, the different quality and thickness of ff. 370-371 and the clearly visible thread thackets between f. 378 and f. 379, make it likely that there are two different quires: a quire that consists of 2 bifolia only and has one missing leaf (Quire 35) followed by a regular sexternion (Quire 36). Due to the fact that the manuscript is tightly bound, it is not possible to establish a fully verifiable collation. While James adds that his collation is not practicable, the collation in this record is partially also a suggestion in lieu of codicological evidence.

While James considers this manuscript a compsoite that consists of four separate codicologial units (ff. 1r-270v [Part 1]; ff. 271r-304v [Part 2]; ff. 305r-357v [Part 3]; ff. 358r-385v [Part 4]), this collation considers the manuscript a single unit that was probably produced over a longer period of time (years if not decades) but probably within the same university context.

catchwords.seg: Catchwords in the lower right-hand margins of the last versos of quires.

layout.seg: Ruled in leadpoint, red ink, or no visible ruling, frame only, sometimes with line ruling visible (e.g. ff. 269v-270r). Single columns (except ff 1r, 271r-272v, 309v-330v, and 360v-365vwhich have two columns. 30-45 lines to the page, written below top line.

handNote.p: Copied by various hands in cursive scripts with Anglicana features.

decoNote.p: Numerous diagrams in brown and red ink (and once with blue on f. 136v) throughout the manuscript; most contain with geometric figures, mainly relating to astronomy, but some feature identifiable objects such as vessels (f. 314v), and a church and defensive towers (ff. 317vâ320r).
Diagrams of star constellations in brown and red ink on ff. 120r-121v.
Large (2 lines) plain red initials throughout the manuscript.
Paraphs in red ink throughout the manuscript.
Underlining in red ink throughout the manuscript.

note.p: Plant material (straw) in the gutters throughout the manuscript, e.g. between ff. 126v-127r, ff. 213-214, and ff. 302v-303r.
Quire numbers in pencil added to the lower right hand corners of the first rectos of quires (no longer followed).

binding.p: Late 18th- or early 19th-century quarter leather binding: paper over pasteboard with a brown leather spine with 6 raised bands, gold-tooling, and a red leather label with the gold-stamped title inscription: TRACTS M.S..

origin.p: Possibly written in various stages from the beginning to about the middle of the 14th century, cf. tables from 1310 onwards on ff. 37r-40r and from 1311 onwards on ff. 105r-107r; an almanac for 1324-1343 on ff. 193r-200r; planetary tables for 1348 on ff. 214r-217r; the years 1349, 1352, and 1356 are mentioned on f. 213v; the Equatorium on ff. 217v-220v dates to c. 1350.

provenance.p: Adam Easton (c. 1330-1397) Easton, Adam, -1397, Benedictine monk and scholar: possibly acquired by him when he studied at Gloucester College, Oxford.

Donated to Norwich Cathedral PrioryNorwich Priory (Norwich, England) by Adam Easton (c. 1330-1397) Easton, Adam, -1397: pressmark 'X Clxx' on f. 1r. The letter 'X' was allocated to Easton's donations (see: Ker, 'Medieval Manuscripts from Norwich Cathedral Priory' (1949), p. 21; Ker, Medieval Libraries of Great Britain (1964), p. 136).
John Style (fl. 16th century) Style, John: their name inscribed on f. [i] recto: 'Jhon Style' [3x] and: 'Jhon' (erased).
William David (fl. 16th century) David, William: their name inscribed on f. [i] recto: 'willelmus David' and: 'Wyllyam' (in a different hand), possibly followed by a classmark: '33'.
Thomas Knyvett (c.1539-1618) Knyvett, Thomas, c.1539-1618, of Ashwellthorpe: no. 56 in his library as indicated by the classmark on f. 391v: 'Sed - 56' (see McKitterick (1978), p. 163 [no. 56]).

John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : no. 238 (this number inscribed on f. [i] recto) in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now CUL Oo.7.50.2, compiled by Thomas Tanner (1674-1735) Tanner, Thomas, 1674-1735 after the publication of Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum AngliÃ¦ et HiberniÃ¦ (c. 1697).

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 : donation bookplate engraved by John Pine Pine, John, 1690-1756 in 1736 on the inside of the front cover.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on and an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1926 and 1930 by M.R. James James, M.R. (Montague Rhodes), 1862-1936, now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/74); Patrick Zutshi, 'Adam Easton's Manuscripts', in Cardinal Adam Easton (c. 1330-1397), ed. by Patrick Zutshi (Amsterdam: Amsterdam University Press, 2020), pp. 206-223 (pp. 217-220 [no. 7]); and David Juste, MS Cambridge, University Library, Gg 6.3 (1572), in Ptolemaeus Arabus et Latinus [Update: 02-03-2022]

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
